social_posts.post_text: We’ve reached my favorite time of the year, which is when I share my favorite photos from each round of Formula Drift. Without further ado, here’s Long Beach…which, coincidentally, is my favorite track to shoot at every year. 🤗
Did a little test stream at the shop the other day, thank you to everyone that hung out with me while we went over updates 🥰 Will be doing more soon with the YEET36!

For my next series of favorites from FD22, we have Atlanta. Probably what I consider to be the most dynamic track to shoot, it’s been one of my favorites every year. The sunsets can be consistently unparalleled, or it can rain and become an entirely different place. There’s really nothing like it.
Next up, some favorites from Orlando. I’ve grown accustomed to shooting in the rain in Orlando, but this year probably topped them all! 😅
IT’S HAPPENING!! We’ve started streaming getting to work with the YEET36, but first, @eric_conkling gave it a much needed bath. ❤️🛁

Continuing on with my favorites from FD22 are these selects from New Jersey. This track is really interesting to shoot, because on track you have a lot of opportunities to pan, while you can also walk around the exterior and find a large variety of different angles. I think my favorite is from the starting line, but I am a sucker for a good pan!
Just some booty pics (not clickbait).

Next up from my favorites of this year’s Formula Drift season, we have St. Louis. There’s usually some pretty epic sunsets at this track, and I find myself really stretching my comfort zones when I shoot here due to the unique locations! It’s fun to try to do things a little differently each year!

Seattle has always been one of my favorite FD events to shoot, one of the main reasons being the sunsets (a running theme for me, I know). This track has so many unique points of view, I love coming away with something a little different each year.

I had no idea what to expect for the first time Formula Drift would be in Utah, but this round truly surprised me. I remember poring over the track map trying to decipher where the best locations would be, knowing very little about the landscape that surrounded it. It was so beautiful, and we started early enough for the sunrise each morning and ended with the sunset each night. I loved the mountains, I loved the clouds, I loved the light, I loved the colors. I can’t wait to go back, there’s so much more to shoot there.
So grateful to share my life with yours. @eric_conkling ❤️
I’ve struggled heavily with my mental health this year, but looking back at moments like these remind me how sweet life is, even when I’m feeling so low. Here’s to 2023. ❤️

Closing out my favorite photos from FD22 — Irwindale. One of the first Formula Drift events I attended, and a track I’ve been shooting at since I began in 2014, Irwindale has always held a special place in my heart. I’ve learned so much here, from panning to night shooting and pushing myself to find ways to do something differently than before.

I hope you enjoyed these as much as I enjoyed sharing then. It’s fun to take a step back and look at what I did throughout a year, reminding myself that I am always growing. ❤️
I’ve always been pretty self conscious about my editing because we all have our own styles, but it is fun to see how it started and how it ended.

34. I feel as though I’ve lived many lifetimes, but I guess that’s just a part of getting older. I wish I could tell my 17 year old self that the things that seem super important will change, that pain is only temporary, and that she will one day love her face and her body. We’ve made growing older into something to fear or resent, but there’s not a single day that I would ever want to be 17 again. I feel more fulfilled, more free, and more confident with each day…aging is a privilege we aren’t always given, and there’s so much I could have missed out on. ❤️

(ty @eric_conkling for being my creative director & photographer)

Here’s something that I find pretty neat — this week I’ll be heading into my tenth season shooting at Formula Drift! Not to be sentimental (ok, maybe a little sentimental) but, I don’t think I ever could have envisioned where photography would take me, specifically through Formula Drift. TW // Pet Loss

One year ago today I was forced to make the difficult decision to let Xerxes go. It was genuinely the worst day of my life. I remember every painful detail, and what hurts is how easily I can remember the sadness, but how difficult it is to remember something like what he sounded like. I was dying my hair, I had it up in clips and parted and I looked so stupid as it dried and crusted at the vet’s office. I was wearing a Britney Spears t-shirt and he drooled and got orange cat hair all over it. I didn’t wash it, I just packed it in a case with all of his stuff. I haven’t seen it since. I cried so much my mask was soaked with tears and snot and I remember being unable to even say anything after the moment I screamed for my mom’s help to take me to the vet. My mom did so much for me in that moment, she really is one of the strongest people I know.

Every moment has felt empty without him. I have spent countless hours crying, looking at photos and videos, wishing I had taken more. I didn’t take enough. I have spent so much time thinking of every moment I could have done something different, because to this day I feel like I failed him. I think I’ll always feel that way.

It’s hard to believe it has only been a year, but at the same time it feels as if it has been an eternity since I lost him. I always thought we would have more time together, but in the time we did have, he was my world, my stabilizing force, my comfort. I can only hope that he knew how much I loved him.

I haven’t really been ok for the last year. I know grief is something that never really goes away, but some days it really is hard. I used to love being home alone, but now it makes me lonely. I’ve felt myself pull inwards more over the past year, and even when I am happy, I feel the gnawing pain of loss. I don’t feel like myself most days, but I’m grateful for the support and understanding those closest to me give me. I hope one day it gets easier.

I love you and miss you Xerxes. Until we meet again, baby boy. ❤️

So genuinely grateful to have been given the opportunity to share my story with @kristenleeeeeeee and @motortrend as part of AAPI Heritage Month! Even after all this time working as a photographer in this space, I still feel like that little girl that didn’t know much about cameras and photography, but loved to capture memories. As a mixed race kid, I spent a lot of time feeling that I didn’t belong to either side of my heritage and struggled with my identity due to this. It means so much to have been included in the discussion and representation with my fellow Asian American brothers and sisters, and it is truly an honor to be a part of this series.

In just over a week, I’ll be heading out to California for the eighth and final round this year of Formula Drift. As I said at the beginning of this season, this is my tenth season shooting FD, which is still completely mind boggling to me! Every one of those years I shot Irwindale, and if I could find and share everything I’ve ever taken there, I would, but these will have to do for now haha. So much of my life has been shaped by learning to shoot and doing just a few rounds that first year, and it’s hard to believe where photography (and FD specifically) has taken me, truly. ❤️

Years ago, my old manager, who really became a mentor to me, @stevenstone, gave me a piece of his wisdom that stuck with me. He said, "You're not just taking photos; you're telling a story." That changed the way I looked at photography.

Throughout the 2023 Formula Drift Season, spanning all 8 rounds, I had the privilege of witnessing the full spectrum of emotions – the highs and lows, the heartache and elation – as drivers poured their hearts into the pursuit of victory. This weekend, we saw a dreamer win his first-ever event at #FDIRW.@NickNoback gave it his all, and I knew I had to capture the moment. At the podium ceremony, @jaroddeanda handed the microphone to Nick. After expressing gratitude to his team, sponsors, and loved ones. He dedicated his win to his late friend Keith. You could feel the emotions mixing in the crowd when his eyes teared up, knowing he had made Keith proud. We all felt it.

Huge congratulations to Nick and his team. You guys truly earned it! 🏆

#DoItForKeith #YouDidItForKeith

Also want to give a shoutout to @CaitlinShoots, who's been documenting Nick all year long. As the night went on and Nick kept defeating his opponents, the joy when I saw her face when was working his way to the top of the box was priceless.
Absolutely amazing weekend. 🏆

This was my tenth season shooting Formula Drift Irwindale ❤️

When I first started, I was just a girl learning how to hold a camera and play around with settings because shooting was the most fun thing I had ever done and provided an escape from a job that emotionally drained me. I had no direction, I got a degree because that was the expectation. I was going to pursue a Master’s because I didn’t know what I wanted to do, and staying in school longer would help me prolong the inevitable.

However, I was introduced to photography, more specifically, shooting drifting. And for the first time in a long time, I found something that I could create that made me happy. It was through that first year of Formula Drift that I was able to learn and grow as a photographer, and the next year, I was given a chance to really prove myself through work. I never imagined people would take a chance on me, it was originally not my intention to turn this into a career.

That’s not to say that it has been easy. It’s been a struggle year after year in multiple ways, but it’s one that I find worth having. As I got closer to ten seasons, I started to tell myself “just make it to ten” every time I felt like giving up, which is something I have felt many, many times. This series has provided me so much growth as a person and a photographer, I’ve met so many people and made so many friends I wouldn’t have otherwise. I’ve experienced extreme highs and lows, love and heartbreak, and being able to express myself through photography is the most rewarding thing I have ever had the chance to do. Additionally, what a tremendous honor it is to be able to capture moments in time for others, their own highs and lows. There’s nothing I love to do more.

I can’t believe that I’ve made it through ten seasons. 2014 Caitlin would never believe all the opportunities and things that I have done since first learning how to shoot. My life has been forever changed thanks to Formula Drift, and I know how sappy that sounds, but it’s undeniably true. I’m so grateful for all the chances I’ve been given, all the advice I’ve received from photographers much better than myself, and all the encouragement from others when they didn’t know how badly I needed it at the time.

It’s that time! I love going through and picking out my favorite photos over the year and reminiscing. I’ll be sharing these and more throughout December! ❤️

Starting off my favorite photos from this year with Formula Drift Long Beach.

Long Beach has been my favorite round to shoot since the first year I started. While it remains the same, it’s challenging. There’s a lot of fences, there’s a lot of people (media and spectators), and perhaps one of my bigger challenges is figuring out how to bring something different to my photos each year. This goes for all the tracks, but when it comes to an iconic one such as Long Beach, I find myself stressing out about how I can personally progress more than usual. Fortunately, I have some amazing friends that also want to stretch their creative limits, and coming back to this first round is a great place to help one another with ideas.

I equate this first round to coming back to summer camp every year, seeing familiar faces you haven’t in a long time, and meeting new people. It feels so good to be back every time.

Sidenote: it was so hard to do just ten slides, I could go on and on for this round honestly.

Next up in my series of favorite photos from 2023 is Formula Drift Atlanta.

This track is truly a unique experience and it’s a treat for me to come back year after year. Due to the size of the track (there is so much walking…like…sooo much), there is a lot of room to move around and get different shots. The spectator view even allows for great photos, the possibilities are endless here.

While I do have a lot of variety to choose from for my favorite photos, the thing I love most about Atlanta is the range of pans I can get, so overall I chose to highlight those. Panning has been my favorite thing to do since day one, and Atlanta gives me some of my best ones every year.

If I’m being honest, I have a real love/hate relationship with the FD Orlando rounds. Between the heat, humidity, and inevitable rain, Orlando always comes with its own set of challenges. Orlando is where I first learned what it takes to shoot in the rain, how to find different angles when access is limited, and just how dirty and covered in tire I can really get. 😅

One of my favorite aspects about this track, however, is how close everything is. This came in extra handy this year, because I finally did something that I’ve always wanted to do. It may sound like a minor thing, but I’ve never had the right moment to shoot during a driver’s competition time out. I’ve always wanted to be there for the action, but it generally is a long run, or I have other people I need to stay ok track and cover. So when I had the time and proximity to run back and forth on and off track to cover Kazuya’s, I took that opportunity to capture it. Moments like those, where you see the team work together to get the car back on track, are part of what makes drifting special to me.

Taking a mini break from my favorite FD 2023 photos to share a set of my favorite photos of @eric_conkling this year. :)

I feel so lucky to be able to combine and share what he and I are both so passionate about. Documenting his hard work and dedication to building cars and driving is my favorite thing that I get to do. ❤️

Next up in my favorite Formula Drift 2023 photos is New Jersey.

There is so much to cover at this round, as it is a Pro/ProSpec one, so I find myself running all over…more than usual. 😅 While I love being in the infield boxes so I can get some nice pans, my favorite spots are actually around the perimeter of the track. I spend the weekend bouncing around different spots all over, similarly to Atlanta, this is a fantastic spectator track. I love using the 400 2.8 in cases that I can get super tight shots, and this track caters to that perfectly.

(Another set of photos that made it hard to pick just 10 slides. 😩)

Favorites from St. Louis!

St. Louis is a tough track to shoot. It feels as though we’re pretty much guaranteed rain at some point as well as some serious heat and humidity. I plan my days and routes every round, but this track definitely requires me to make a solid one. However, there is a large variety of shots due to the different shooting locations and the distances between them, which is awesome! There’s also almost always an insanely beautiful sunset each year, which you know I can never resist.

This year was a little rough because there was a whole lot of rain and lightning, resulting in a plethora of delays. Saturday ended up being an extremely long day with the remainder of Prospec and Pro being in the same day, but there is really something about shooting a trophy ceremony in the middle of the day, I was obsessed with the light. 😅

More than halfway through my series of favorite Formula Drift photos from 2023, which brings us to Seattle!

Seattle has been one of my favorite events since I started shooting, I always loved the diversity of media locations and (most of the time) the weather. This track has one of the best sunsets year after year, I will always stay to be sure I capture it. ☺️

Nearing the end of reviewing my favorite photos of the year, we have Salt Lake City.

To me, this track is characterized by extremely early mornings, mountains, and dirt, so much dirt haha. It is, in my opinion, one of the most picturesque tracks we go to in FD, and starting so early in the morning means we get incredible light at the beginning and the end of day. There is a lot of area to cover, which sure, is a lot of walking, but there’s a shot from almost anywhere! This is definitely the dirtiest track to shoot, and not from rubber. 😅 I finish the weekend with a nice layer of dust and dirt caked onto all my gear, but I think that’s a small price to pay to shoot somewhere as beautiful as this.

Wrapping up my series of favorite photos from 2023 with FD Irwindale. ☺️

Probably one of the most iconic FD tracks, Irwindale is a treat to come back to year after year. The first year I was introduced to drifting, I went to this event as a spectator, and had the great fortune to shoot it the following year! This track has so many fantastic spots, but I think my favorite place to shoot has consistently been on the roof. Most days at sunset you can see the LA skyline in the distance, and the sun setting over the track is unreal from up there. I also just go wild for 400 pans from up there, they’re simply 🤌🏼
